# H. Probabilistic derivation of the overlap model 

Here we provide detailed derivations of the exponential model for the interaction between force generators and the astral MTs. We present two different approaches. One is a direct, explicit derivation with all the hypothesis of the problem and substantial algebraic details, and the other simpler calculation making an analogy to picking balls of different colors, with less details. To simplify the notation, we introduce the following events

- $\mathbf{A}_{\mathbf{Y}}=\mathrm{MT}$ hits $\mathrm{CFG}_{\mathbf{Y}}$ (CFG centered at point $\mathbf{Y}$ )
- $\mathbf{B}_{\mathbf{Y}}=\mathrm{MT}$ binds to $\mathrm{CFG}_{\mathbf{Y}}$
- $\mathbf{C}_{\mathbf{Y}}=\mathrm{CFG}_{\mathbf{Y}}$ is occupied
- $\mathbf{D}_{\mathbf{Y}}^{n}=$ There are $n$ other CFG competing for the same MT that already binds to a $\mathrm{CFG}_{\mathbf{Y}}$

Note that in this notation $P(\mathbf{Y})=\mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{C}_{\mathbf{Y}}\right)$.
Let $U$ be a patch over the surface $\Gamma$, centered at $\mathbf{Y}$, of area $A_{U}$ such that $\forall \mathbf{X} \in U$, $|P(\mathbf{X})-P(\mathbf{Y})|<<1$. In the patch the total number of force generators is given by $N_{U}=$ $M \int_{U} \rho(\mathbf{X}) d A \approx M A_{U} \rho(\mathbf{Y})$. To start the derivation we see that the change in $P(\mathbf{Y})$ in a

time-step $\Delta t$ is given by

$$
d P(\mathbf{Y})=-\kappa P(\mathbf{Y}) \Delta t+\mathbb{P}\left(\mathrm{MT} \text { binds to } \mathrm{CFG}_{\mathbf{Y}} \text { in } \Delta t\right)
$$

By the law of total probabilities, we have

$$
\mathbb{P}\left(\mathrm{MT} \text { binds to } \mathrm{CFG}_{\mathbf{Y}} \text { in } \Delta t\right)=\Omega(\mathbf{Y}) \mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{B}_{\mathbf{Y}} \mid \mathbf{A}_{\mathbf{Y}}\right) \Delta t
$$

The details of modeling CFG will be expressed through the term $\mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{B}_{\mathbf{Y}} \mid \mathbf{A}_{\mathbf{Y}}\right)$. For stochiometric interactions, i.e., a free astral MT cannot bind to a CFG that is already occupied, we have $\mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{B}_{\mathbf{Y}} \mid \mathbf{C}_{\mathbf{Y}}\right)=0$. Therefore, by the law of total probabilities, we have

$$
\mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{B}_{\mathbf{Y}} \mid \mathbf{A}_{\mathbf{Y}}\right)=(1-P(\mathbf{Y})) \mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{B}_{\mathbf{Y}} \mid \mathbf{A}_{\mathbf{Y}}, \mathbf{C}_{\mathbf{Y}}^{c}\right)
$$

We first note that if there was no interaction with other CFGs, then $\mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{B}_{\mathbf{Y}} \mid \mathbf{C}_{\mathbf{Y}}^{c}\right)=1$, yielding the independent motor model. However in this work we consider situations where there can be overlap between CFGs. To be specific we consider that if a MT hits a point where there is an overlap between $n$ unoccupied CFGs, this MT will bind randomly to only one of these. In terms of probabilities, it means that $\mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{B}_{\mathbf{Y}} \mid \mathbf{A}_{\mathbf{Y}}, \mathbf{C}_{\mathbf{Y}}, \mathbf{D}_{\mathbf{Y}}^{n}\right)=\frac{1}{1+n}$. Now, for a $\mathrm{CFG}_{\mathbf{X}}$ to be available to compete for the MT it needs to be unbound and there has to be overlap between $\mathrm{CFG}_{\mathbf{X}}$ and $\mathrm{CFG}_{\mathbf{Y}}$. Since these two events are independent, we just need to approximate the probability that there is overlap between different CFGs in the patch $U$. For this we do a simple homogeneity approximation. From here we can see that $D_{\mathbf{Y}}^{n}$ is a binomial distribution (in $n$ ) of parameters $\left(N_{U}-1, \frac{a}{A_{u}}(1-P(Y))\right.$ ), where $a=\pi r_{m}^{2}$ is the discal area of the CFG binding domain. In other words we have

$$
\mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{D}_{\mathbf{Y}}^{n} \mid \mathbf{A}_{\mathbf{Y}}\right)=\binom{N_{U}-1}{n}\left((1-P) \frac{a}{A_{u}}\right)^{n}\left(1-(1-P) \frac{a}{A_{u}}\right)^{N_{U}-1-n}
$$

Putting these together using the law of total probabilities, we then have to evaluate the sum

$$
\mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{B}_{\mathbf{Y}} \mid \mathbf{A}_{\mathbf{Y}}\right)=(1-P(\mathbf{Y})) \sum_{n=0}^{N_{U}-1} \frac{1}{1+n}\binom{N_{U}-1}{n}\left((1-P) \frac{a}{A_{u}}\right)^{n}\left(1-(1-P) \frac{a}{A_{u}}\right)^{N_{U}-1-n}
$$

This sum can be easily evaluated by first letting $q=\left(1-P(\mathbf{Y}) \frac{a}{A_{U}}\right)$ and $J=N_{U}-1$, then we have

$$
\sum_{n=0}^{J}\binom{J}{n} \frac{q^{n}}{n+1}(1-q)^{J-n}=\frac{1}{q} \int_{0}^{q} \sum_{n=0}^{J}\binom{J}{n} x^{n}(1-q)^{J-n} d x
$$

Using Newton's binomial theorem and integrating, we obtain the final expression

$$
\mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{B}_{\mathbf{Y}} \mid \mathbf{A}_{\mathbf{Y}}\right)=\frac{1}{N_{U} \frac{a}{A_{u}}}\left(1-(1-(1-P) \frac{a}{A_{u}})^{N_{U}}\right)
$$

From this expression, we obtain the following three interesting results.

1. If there is no overlap between CFGs, $A_{u}=a$ and $N_{U}=1$, and we recover the independent CFG model where

$$
\mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{B}_{\mathbf{Y}} \mid \mathbf{A}_{\mathbf{Y}}\right)=1-P
$$

2. Taking the limit when $\frac{a}{A_{u}} \rightarrow 0$ we obtain the interaction probability $\mathcal{I}(P)$ used in this work

$$
\mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{B}_{\mathbf{Y}} \mid \mathbf{A}_{\mathbf{Y}}\right)=\frac{1-e^{-a M \rho(1-P)}}{a M \rho}=\mathcal{I}(P)
$$

3. If the CFGs are perfectly stacked one over each other (instead of being randomly distributed), this means that $N_{U}$ is independent of $a$, so we can just call it $N$ and we get

$$
\mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{B}_{\mathbf{Y}} \mid \mathbf{A}_{\mathbf{Y}}\right)=\frac{1-P^{N}}{N}
$$

Below we present a second derivation, simpler in the algebra, that hides many of the details of the interactions. First we define the event

$$
\mathbf{E}_{U}=\text { MT hits patch } U
$$

using law of total probabilities we have

$$
\mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{B}_{\mathbf{Y}} \mid \mathbf{E}_{U}\right)=\mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{B}_{\mathbf{Y}} \mid \mathbf{E}_{U}, \mathbf{A}_{\mathbf{Y}}\right) \mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{A}_{\mathbf{Y}} \mid \mathbf{E}_{U}\right)+\mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{B}_{\mathbf{Y}} \mid \mathbf{E}_{U}, \mathbf{A}_{\mathbf{Y}}^{C}\right) \mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{A}_{\mathbf{Y}}^{C} \mid \mathbf{E}_{U}\right)
$$

The probability of binding to $\mathrm{CFG}_{\mathbf{Y}}$ with no MT hitting the area that it covers, is 0 . Further, conditioning over $\mathbf{E}_{U}$ and $\mathbf{A}_{\mathbf{Y}}$ is redundant, since the latter implies the former. Thus the expression is simplified to

$$
\mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{B}_{\mathbf{Y}} \mid \mathbf{E}_{U}\right)=\mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{B}_{\mathbf{Y}} \mid \mathbf{A}_{\mathbf{Y}}\right) \mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{A}_{\mathbf{Y}} \mid \mathbf{E}_{U}\right)
$$

We are interested in (re)determining $\mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{B}_{\mathbf{Y}} \mid \mathbf{A}_{\mathbf{Y}}\right)$, but $\mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{B}_{\mathbf{Y}} \mid \mathbf{E}_{U}\right)$ has the advantage that every CFG within patch $U$ can be treated equally. To simplify the computation of this

quantity, we set up an equivalent but simpler problem. Take $N_{U}$ balls, with one of them being red, and put them in two different boxes, each ball with probability $(1-P) \frac{a}{A_{u}}$ being in box one, and in the other box with the complement probability. Next, one ball is picked from box one (if there is any ball). We pose the question: What is the probability that the red ball is picked?

It is not difficult to see that getting the red ball has a probability of $\mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{B}_{\mathbf{Y}} \mid \mathbf{E}_{U}\right)$. In this setting, we just need to determine the probability that there is at least one ball in box one and that the picked ball is red. Since all of the balls are the same, these two probabilities are independent, so it is straightforward that

$$
\mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{B}_{\mathbf{Y}} \mid \mathbf{E}_{U}\right)=\frac{1}{N_{U}}\left(1-(1-(1-P) \frac{a}{A_{u}})^{N_{U}}\right)
$$

Noting that $\mathbb{P}\left(\mathbf{A}_{\mathbf{Y}} \mid \mathbf{E}_{U}\right)=\frac{a}{A_{U}}$ finalizes the proof.

# I. Aster dynamics inside a cuboid 

We conducted simulations of the S-model with a centrosome placed inside a cuboid of dimensions $15 \times 15 \times 3 \mu \mathrm{~m}$ with CFGs positioned exclusively on the peripheral sides (see Fig. 12A), imitating the microchamber in the experiments [14-16]. For a given characteristic MT length, we compute the pulling force distribution minus the force needed to keep the centrosome at a given point inside the chamber. When the average MT length $\left(l_{c}=20 \mu m\right)$ is comparable to the length of the microchamber, a singular fixed point emerges at the chamber's center (Fig. 12B). For shorter MTs, a constellation of fixed points appears, distributed around the central region (Fig. 12C). The central fixed point becomes unstable, while eight additional fixed points formed, with those near the chamber's corners exhibiting stability (red in Fig. 12C), and the intermediates acting as saddle points (yellow in Fig. 12C). Previous theoretical models successfully explained the positioning of the aster in these microchambers by a balance of pulling forces from motors and pushing forces from MT growth and friction with the chamber periphery [14-16]. Our findings provide an alternative explanation for the positioning of centrosomes in microchambers, suggesting it results from the combined effect of pulling forces and the stoichiometric interactions between MTs and molecular motors.

abstract:
The centrosomal aster is a mobile cellular organelle that exerts and
transmits forces necessary for nuclear migration and spindle positioning.
Recent experimental and theoretical studies of nematode and human cells
demonstrate that pulling forces on asters by cortical force generators are
dominant during such processes. We present a comprehensive investigation of a
first-principles model of aster dynamics, the S-model (S for stoichiometry),
based solely on such forces. The model evolves the astral centrosome position,
a probability field of cell-surface motor occupancy by centrosomal microtubules
(under an assumption of stoichiometric binding), and free boundaries of
unattached, growing microtubules. We show how cell shape affects the centering
stability of the aster, and its transition to oscillations with increasing
motor number. Seeking to understand observations in single-cell nematode
embryos, we use accurate simulations to examine the nonlinear structures of the
bifurcations, and demonstrate the importance of binding domain overlap to
interpreting genetic perturbation experiments. We find a rich dynamical
landscape, dependent upon cell shape, such as internal equatorial orbits of
asters that can be seen as traveling wave solutions. Finally, we study the
interactions of multiple asters and demonstrate an effective mutual repulsion
due to their competition for cortical force generators. We find, amazingly,
that asters can relax onto the vertices of platonic and non-platonic solids,
closely mirroring the results of the classical Thomson problem for
energy-minimizing configurations of electrons constrained to a sphere and
interacting via repulsive Coulomb potentials. Our findings both explain
experimental observations, providing insights into the mechanisms governing
spindle positioning and cell division dynamics, and show the possibility of new
nonlinear phenomena in cell biology.
